'''Arthur Cheney Train''' (September 6, 1875 &ndash; December 22, 1945), also called '''Arthur Chesney Train''', was an American [[lawyer]] and writer of [[legal thrillers]], particularly known for his novels of [[courtroom]] intrigue and the creation of the fictional lawyer Mr. Ephraim Tutt.<ref name="ATObit1945"/>

==Early life==
Train was born in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] on September 6, 1875. His father was lawyer [[Charles Russell Train]], who served for many years as attorney general of Massachusetts, and his mother was Sara Maria Cheney.<ref name="ATObit1945"/>

After attending [[St. Paul's School (New Hampshire)|St. Paul's School]] in [[Concord, New Hampshire]], Train graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] from [[Harvard University]] in 1896 and [[LLB]] from [[Harvard Law School]] in 1899.<ref name="ANB">Schmid (1999)</ref>

==Career==
In January 1901, Train became assistant in the office of the [[New York County District Attorney]]. In 1904 he started his literary career with the publication of the [[short story]] "The Maximilian Diamond" in ''[[The American Magazine|Leslie's Monthly]]''. He ran the two careers in parallel until 1908 when he left the District Attorney's office to open a general law practice in the Mutual Life Building at 34 Nassau Street in New York City.<ref name="ANB"/> His 1907 novel, ''Mortmain'', was one of the earliest works in the [[alien hand syndrome]] genre and was adapted into a 1915 film of the same name that is now [[lost film|lost]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mortmain|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/AbbrView.aspx?s=1&Movie=16569|publisher=American Film Institute Catalog|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref> Several other works by Train were filmed, including ''[[Illusion (1929 film)|Illusion]]'' (1929), ''[[His Children's Children]]'' (1923), and ''[[The Blind Goddess]]'' (1926).<ref name="Munden">{{cite book |last1=American Film Institute |editor1-last=Munden |editor1-first=Kenneth White |title=The American Film Institute Catalog of Motion Pictures Produced in the United States, Part 1 |date=1997 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=9780520209695 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=rlLbRAPOgP0C&pg=PA375&dq=%22Arthur+Chesney+Train%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi23o2X6treAhXQfCsKHeSFBuw4ChDoAQg3MAM#v=onepage&q=%22Arthur%20Chesney%20Train%22&f=false}}</ref>

From 1915 to 1922, Train was in private practice as a lawyer with [[Charles A. Perkins|Charles Albert Perkins]] while continuing to write, not just novels but short stories, plays, and [[journalism]]. In 1919, he created the popular character of Mr. Ephraim Tutt, a wily old lawyer who supported the common man and always had a trick up his sleeve to right the law's injustices.<ref name="ANB"/>

Train wrote dozens of stories about Tutt in the ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]''. The fictional Ephraim Tutt became "the best known lawyer in America," particularly after the appearance of ''Yankee Lawyer,'' an immensely popular book that purported to be Tutt's autobiography. Train also coauthored two [[science fiction]] novels with eminent [[physicist]] [[Robert W. Wood]].<ref>Train & Wood (1915), (1916)</ref> After 1922, he devoted himself to writing.<ref name="ANB"/><ref>Schmid, D. (1999) "Train, Arthur", ''[[American National Biography]]'', Oxford University Press, '''21''': 799-800, {{ISBN|0-19-520635-5}}</ref><ref>Train, A. C. (1939) ''My Day in Court'', New York: Charles Scribner's Sons: Arthur Train's autobiography</ref>

==Personal life==
In 1897, Train married Ethel Kissam (1876–1923). Ethel was the daughter of Benjamin Kissam and Lucy ([[née]] Warren) Kissam, the niece of [[William Henry Vanderbilt|Maria (née Kissam) Vanderbilt]] and the first cousin of [[William Kissam Vanderbilt|William]], [[Cornelius Vanderbilt II|Cornelius]], [[Margaret Louisa Vanderbilt|Margaret]], [[Emily Thorn Vanderbilt|Emily]], [[Florence Adele Vanderbilt Twombly|Florence]], [[Frederick William Vanderbilt|Frederick]], [[Eliza Osgood Vanderbilt Webb|Eliza]], and [[George Washington Vanderbilt II]]. Together, they had four children, including Arthur Kissam Train.<ref name="ANB"/>

Ethel died in 1923 and Train married Helen Coster Gerard in 1926, with whom he had one child [[John Train (investment advisor)|John Train]].<ref name="ANB"/>

Train died on December 22, 1945 in New York City.<ref name="ATObit1945">{{cite news |title=ARTHUR TRAIN DEAD; CREATED 'MR. TUTT'; Turned Law Experiences Into Series of Stories Featuring Friend of Widow, Orphan MANY DECEIVED BY HERO Offered Him Large Retainers --Former W.T. Jerome Aide Headed National Institute Letters for Mr. Tutt Appointed by Governor Hughes |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1945/12/23/107129973.pdf |accessdate=13 July 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 23, 1945 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="1945Rites">{{cite news |title=RITES FOR ARTHUR TRAIN; Private Funeral Service to Be Held Today-Body Cremated |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1945/12/24/88325877.html?pageNumber=15 |accessdate=13 July 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 24, 1945 |language=en}}</ref>

