In September 1994, President [[Bill Clinton]] signed into law the '''Home Ownership and Equity Protection Act of 1994''', written by US Rep. [[Joseph P. Kennedy II|Joseph P. Kennedy]] (D-Mass). The law requires certain disclosures and clamps restrictions on lenders of high-cost loans.<ref>"Some new protection on homeowner loans," Oct 13, 1994, The Boston Globe, Real Estate, p. A1</ref><ref>http://apps.americanbar.org/buslaw/committees/CL130000pub/newsletter/200708/natter.pdf</ref>
Implemented via Regulation Z at 12 CFR 226.32, it only applies to non-purchase-money transactions.
The law gives the [[Federal Reserve Board]] the power to administer the act and to adjust the implementing regulations. Critics of [[Alan Greenspan]] argue that he failed to properly use these powers when [[subprime mortgage]] problems became apparent in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/159346|title=Hirsh: Greenspan's To Blame for Wall Street Woes|date=16 September 2008|publisher=}}</ref>
