t in Lithuania|Lithuania]] have ever used this as a capital punishment method. Now legal in some U.S. states only to replace injection at the request of the prisoner or if injection is impractical. Also used in Nazi Germany during World War 2 as a weapon for [[The Holocaust|mass murder]]. It has been recently proposed to use [[nitrogen hypoxia]] to replace injection. |- | align="center" | [[Beheading]]|| Has been used at various points in history in many countries. One of the most famous forms is execution by [[guillotine]]. Now used only in [[Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia|Saudi Arabia]] with a sword. |- | align="center" | [[Stoning]]|| The condemned is pummeled by stones thrown by a group of people with the totality of the injuries suffered leading to eventual death. |- | align="center" | [[Crucifixion]]|| Roping or nailing to a wooden cross or similar apparatus (such as a tree) and allowing to perish.{{Where|date= November 2018|talk=yes}} |- |}
== Ancient methods == {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! '''Method''' !! Description |- | align="center" | [[Animal]]s || * [[Execution by elephant|Crushing by elephant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neatorama.com/2007/05/29/this-wont-hurt-a-bit-a-painlessly-short-and-incomplete-evolution-of-execution/|title=This Won't Hurt a Bit: A Painlessly Short (and Incomplete) Evolution of Execution.|author=|date=|website=neatorama.com}}</ref> * Devouring by animals, as in ''[[damnatio ad bestias]]'' (i.e., as in the [[cliché]], "being thrown to the lions"), as well as by [[alligator]]s, [[crocodile]]s, [[piranha]] and [[shark]]s. * Stings from scorpions and bites by snakes, spiders, etc. (e.g. the "[[Snake pit]]" of Germanic legend){{Dubious|date=September 2012}}<!--We should have at least one non-legendary account in which a person is *sentenced to death* by venomous bite. Otherwise this entry ought to be removed, and sooner than in two years from now.--> * Tearing apart by horses (''e.g.'', in [[Middle Ages|medieval]] Europe and [[History of China#Imperial era|Imperial China]], with four horses; or "[[Hanged, drawn and quartered|quartering]]", with four horses, as in ''[[The Song of Roland]]'' and ''[[Child Owlet]]''). * Trampling by horses (example: [[Al-Musta'sim]], the last [[Abbasid]] [[Caliph]] in [[Baghdad]]). |- | align="center" | Back-breaking || A [[Mongolia]]n method of execution that avoided the spilling of blood on the ground<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFx3OlrBMpQC&pg=PA53&dq=Back+broken+mongol|title=The History of the Mongol Conquests|first=J. J.|last=Saunders|date=1 March 2001|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|via=Google Books|page=53}}</ref> (example: the Mongolian leader [[Jamukha]] was probably executed this way in 1206).<ref>''The Secret History of the Mongols'', book 8, chapter 201.</ref> |- | align="center" | [[Blowing from a gun]]||Tied to the mouth of a cannon, which is then fired. |- | align="center" | [[Blood Eagle]]||Cutting the skin of the victim by the spine, breaking the ribs so they resembled blood-stained wings, and pulling the lungs out through the wounds in the victim's back. Used by the [[Vikings]]. |- | align="center" | [[Boiling to death]]||This penalty was carried out using a large cauldron filled with water, oil, tar, tallow, or even molten lead. |- | align="center" | [[Brazen bull]]||Pushed inside an iron bull statue and then cooked alive after a fire is lit under it. |- | align="center" | [[Breaking wheel]]||Also known as the Catherine wheel, after a [[Saint Catherine of Alexandria|saint]] who was allegedly sentenced to be executed by this method. |- | align="center" | [[Premature burial|Buried alive]]||Traditional [[punishment]] for [[Vestal virgins]] who had broken their vows. |- | align="center" | [[Execution by burning|Burning]]||Most infamous as a method of execution for [[Heresy|heretics]] and [[Witchcraft|witches]]. A slower method of applying single pieces of burning wood was used by [[Indigenous peoples of North America|Native Americans]] in torturing their captives to death.<ref>Frederick Drimmer (ed.) ''"Captured by the Indians - 15 Firsthand Accounts, 1750-1870"'', Dover Publications, Mineola, N.Y., 1985.</ref> |- | align="center" | [[Crushing (execution)|Crushing]]|| By a weight, abruptly or as a slow ordeal. |- | align="center" | [[Disembowelment]]||Often employed as a preliminary stage to the actual execution, e.g. by beheading; an integral part of ''[[seppuku]]'' (''harakiri''), which was sometimes used as a form of capital punishment. |- | align="center" | [[Dismemberment]]|| Being [[drawn and quartered]] sometimes resulted in dismemberment. Note: has been used in combination, such as [[hanged, drawn and quartered]] |- | align="center" | [[Hanged, drawn and quartered|Drawing and quartering]]||English method of executing those found guilty of [[high treason]]. |- | align="center" | [[Falling (execution)|Falling]]||The victim is thrown off a height or into a hollow (example: the ''Barathron'' in Athens, into which the Athenian generals condemned for their part in the [[battle of Arginusae]] were cast).<ref>[[Xenophon]], ''"Hellenica"'', book I, chapter VII.</ref> In Argentina during the [[Dirty War]], those [[forced disappearance|secretly abducted]] were later drugged and [[Death flights|thrown from an airplane into the ocean]]. |- | align="center" | [[Flaying]]||The skin is removed from the body. |- | align="center" | [[Garrote]]||Used most commonly in [[Spain]] and in former Spanish colonies (e.g. the [[Philippines]]), used to strangle or choke someone. |- | align="center" | [[Gibbeting]]||The act of gibbeting refers to the use of a gallows-type structure from which the victim was usually placed within a cage which is then hung in a public location and the victim left to die to deter other existing or potential criminals. |- | align="center" | [[Immurement]]||The confinement of a person by walling off any exits; since they were usually kept alive through an opening, this was more a form of [[imprisonment for life]] than of capital punishment (example: the countess [[Elisabeth Báthory]], who lived for four more years after having been immured). |- | align="center" | [[Impalement]]||The penetration of a human by an object such as a stake, pole, spear, or hook, often by complete or partial perforation of the torso. |- |align="center" | [[Keelhauling]]||European maritime punishment. |- | align="center" | [[Poena cullei]]||Documented used during the Roman empire. The condemned is stuffed into a sack together with a number of animals and thrown into a body of water. |- | align="center" | [[Poisoning]] || Before modern times, sayak (사약, 賜藥) was the method of capital punishment of nobles (''[[yangban]]'') and members of the royal family during the [[Joseon Dynasty]] in [[Korea]] due to the [[Confucianist]] belief that one may kill a [[seonbi]] but may not insult him (사가살불가욕, 士可殺不可辱). Poisoning by drinking an infusion of [[Conium maculatum|hemlock]] was used as a method of execution in ancient Greece. |- | align="center" | [[Pendulum (torture device)|Pendulum]]<ref>R.D. Melville (1905), "The Use and Forms of Judicial Torture in England and Scotland," ''The Scottish Historical Review'', vol. 2, p. 228; Geoffrey Abbott (2006) ''Execution: the guillotine, the Pendulum, the Thousand Cuts, the Spanish Donkey, and 66 Other Ways of Putting Someone to Death'', MacMillan, {{ISBN|0-312-35222-0}}, p. 213. Both of these refer to the use of the pendulum (''pendola'')by inquisitorial tribunals. Melville, however, refers only to its use as a torture method, while Abbott suggests that the device was purposely allowed to kill the victim if he refused to confess.</ref> || A type of machine with an axe head for a weight that slices closer to the victim's torso over time. (''Of disputed historicity.'') |- | align="center" | [[Sawing (torture)|Sawing]]||(''Of disputed historicity.'') |- | align="center" | [[Scaphism]]|| An Ancient [[Persian Empire|Persian]] method of execution in which the condemned was placed in between two boats, force fed a mixture of honey and milk, and left floating in a stagnant pond. The victim would then suffer from severe diarrhea, which would attract insects that would burrow, nest, and feed on the victim. The victim would eventually die from [[septic shock]]. |- | align="center" | [[Slow slicing]]||Methodically removing portions of the body over an extended period of time, typically with a knife, eventually resulting in death. |- | align="center" | [[Asphyxia#Smothering|Smothering (Asphyxia)]]|| [[Suffocation in ash]] |- | align="center" | [[Starvation]] / [[Dehydration]]|| [[Immurement]] |- | align="center" | [[Strangling|Strangulation]]|| |- | align="center" | [[Suffocation]]|| * [[Carbon monoxide]] poisoning by burning coal in a sealed room.<ref>Penney, David G. (2000) [https://books.google.com/books?id=XsnPIfP0oBcC&pg=PA5 ''Carbon Monoxide Toxicity''], CRC Press, p. 5, {{ISBN|0-8493-2065-8}}.</ref> |- |}
