The '''United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs''' ('''UNOOSA''') is a part of the [[United Nations Secretariat]], located at the [[United Nations Office in Vienna|United Nations Office]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]. It is tasked with implementing the decisions of the [[United Nations General Assembly]] and of the [[United Nations Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space]].{{fact|date=May 2018}}

== History ==
{{stack|{{expand section|history milestones since 1990s founding should be detailed|date=October 2016}}}}
On {{start date and age|1958|12|13|df=y|paren=y}}, the United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs (UNOOSA) was initially created as a small expert unit within the United Nations Secretariat in New York to assist the ''ad hoc'' Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space established by the General Assembly in its resolution 1348 (XIII).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol%3DA%2FRES%2F1348%28XIII%29 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703011343/http://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A%2FRES%2F1348%28XIII%29 |archivedate=2015-07-03 |df= }}</ref>

In 1962, the unit became positioned within the Department of Political and Security Council Affairs (DPSCA), when the [[UN Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space|Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space]] met for the first time.{{fact|date=May 2018}}

In 1968, the unit was transformed into the Outer Space Affairs Division of DPSCA.{{fact|date=May 2018}}

In 1992, the Division was transformed into the Office for Outer Space Affairs within the [[United Nations Department of Political Affairs|Department for Political Affairs]], relocating to the United Nations Office at Vienna the following year, in 1993.{{fact|date=May 2018}}

In 2005, the International Committee on Global Navigation Satellite Systems (ICG) was established under the umbrella of the United Nations.<ref name="icgnss"/>

In 2006, the [[UN-SPIDER]] programme was established to "provide universal access to all countries and all relevant international and regional organizations to all types of space-based information and services relevant to disaster management to support the full disaster management cycle".<ref name="un-spider.org"/><ref name="spiderresolution">[https://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/61/110&Lang=E General Assembly resolution 61/110]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703011252/http://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A%2FRES%2F61%2F110&Lang=E |date=2015-07-03 }}</ref>

In 2009, [[Takao Doi]] became Chief of Space Applications.{{fact|date=May 2018}}

In 2010, the Human Space Initiative was launched.<ref name="hsi2010"/>

In March 2014, the Secretary-General appointed [[Simonetta Di Pippo]] ([[Italy]]) as the new Director of the Office, having previously served as the Director of Human Spaceflight at the [[European Space Agency]].{{fact|date=May 2018}}

In September 2016, UNOOSA announced the first-ever United Nations space mission, partnering with the [[Sierra Nevada Corporation]] (SNC). Using the SNC [[Dream Chaser]] spaceplane, UNOOSA will enable developing nations to send [[microgravity]] payloads into low-Earth orbit, with a target launch in 2021.<ref name="CSM_Williams">
  {{cite news
  | last=Williams | first=Weston
  | title=Why the United Nations is launching a space mission
  | work=[[Christian Science Monitor]]
  | date=2016-09-29 | accessdate=2016-10-03
  | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0929/Why-the-United-Nations-is-launching-a-space-mission
}}</ref><ref name="UNOOSA_2016-09-27">
  {{cite web
  | title=The United Nations and Sierra Nevada Corporation Announce First Ever Dedicated United Nations―Dream Chaser Space Mission
